Plot 1

Based on the value of Gini Coefficients, the United States is one of the most unequal countries in the OECD. In 2014, it ranked below only three other countries.

Plot 2

This level of income inequality is not new for the United States. For example, US has had a significanlty higher Gini Coefficient than Canada since the 1980s.

Plot 3

Generally, countries with higher income have lower inequality. However, the Unites States is once again an outlier, having the highest income inequality among higher income countries. The US also lags behind OECD countries in terms of public social spending.

Plot 4

```

With a closer focus on inequality within the United States, we can see that the top 5% of earners have nearly 25% of the income share. Over time, more of the income share has gone to the top 20% of earners.

Plot 5

Further patterns of income inequality emerge when earnings are separated by race. Many more Black workers than White and Asian workers earned less than $1000 per week in 2016. The dashed lines show median income for each group - black workers have the lowest median, and the earnings of Asian workers are less skewed than White earners.
